ations of the art. Centered in Germany during the 1920s and 1930s, the movement to create new instruments encompassed a broad spectrum of experiments, from the exploration of microtonal tunings and exotic tone colors to the ability to compose directly for automatic musical machines. This movement comprised composers, inventors, and visual artists, including Paul Hindemith, Ernst Toch, Jörg Mager, Friedrich Trautwein, László Moholy-Nagy, Walter Ruttmann, and Oskar Fischinger. Patteson's fascinating study combines an artifact-oriented history of new music in the early twentieth century with an astute revisiting of still-relevant debates about the relationship between technology and the arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil engineering. 0aCommunication. 0aElectronic musical instrumentsxHistory. 0aEngineering. 0aMass media. 0aMusic and technologyxHistory. 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aMusical instruments. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a20th century music history.  adeveloping new musical instruments.  adeveloping new musical technology.  aelectronic musical instruments.  ahistory of music.  ajorg mager.  amechanical instruments.  amedia instruments.  amusic and technology.  amusic appreciation.  amusic composition.  amusic theory.  amusic.  amusical aesthetics.  amusical automation.  amusical innovation.  amusical inscription.  anew music.  anew musical instruments in the 20th century.  asound technology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/97805209